10-04-2025: I taken knowledge about Transactions, Commit and Rollback in MySQL RDBMS.
A transaction is a sequence of operations performed as a single logical unit of work. In databases, transactions ensure data integrity and consistency.

âœ…Understand What a Transaction Is
   >> A transaction is a group of operations that should be executed as a single unit.
âœ…Example: Bank transfer â€“ debit from one account, credit to another.

âœ…Importance of Transaction Management
  ðŸ”µ Helps in maintaining the consistency and reliability of data.
  ðŸ”µ Crucial for applications that deal with multiple related database operations.

âœ…ACID Properties
ðŸŸ£Learn the four key properties of transactions:
    ðŸ”µAtomicity â€“ All or nothing.
    ðŸ”µConsistency â€“ Data remains valid.
    ðŸ”µIsolation â€“ Transactions donâ€™t affect each other.
    ðŸ”µDurability â€“ Committed changes persist.

âœ…Commit Operation
     ðŸ”µCommit is used to save all the changes made by the transaction permanently in the database.
     ðŸ”µUsed to save all changes permanently.
     ðŸ”µOnce committed, changes cannot be rolled back.

      Example:

       BEGIN TRANSACTION;
       UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
       UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;
       COMMIT;

âœ…Rollback Operation
      ðŸ”µRollback is used to undo all changes made in the current transaction.
      ðŸ”µUsed to undo changes if something goes wrong.
      ðŸ”µHelps prevent corrupt or partial data.
     
     Example: 
               BEGIN TRANSACTION;
               UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;
               -- Something goes wrong here
               ROLLBACK;

     
âœ… Error Handling with Transactions

âœ… Learn how to use try-catch blocks in code (like JDBC in Java) to manage commits and rollbacks safely.

âœ…Real-Life Applications

  Used in banking systems, order processing, inventory updates, etc.


